<p>I recently received a patch that used <code>__DARWIN_C_LEVEL</code>. I think the person providing it uses OS X 10.10.</p>  <p>I have OS 10.9, 10.8 and 10.5 for testing, but none of them appear to define it.</p>  <p><strong><em>10.5</em></strong>:</p>  <pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code>$ uname -a Darwin PowerMac.home.pvt 9.8.0 Darwin Kernel Version 9.8.0: Wed Jul 15 16:57:01 PDT 2009; root:xnu-1228.15.4~1/RELEASE_PPC Power Macintosh $ cpp -dM &lt; /dev/null | grep -i darwin $ </code></pre>  <p><strong><em>10.8</em></strong>:</p>  <pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code>$ uname -a Darwin riemann.home.pvt 12.6.0 Darwin Kernel Version 12.6.0: Wed Mar 18 16:23:48 PDT 2015; root:xnu-2050.48.19~1/RELEASE_X86_64 x86_64 $ cpp -dM &lt;/dev/null | grep -i darwin $ </code></pre>  <p>There are lots of hits for it, but its either a rip of Apple's source code or someone's patch. Confer, <a href="http://www.google.com/search?q=&quot;__DARWIN_C_LEVEL&quot;+site%3Aopensource.apple.com">"__DARWIN_C_LEVEL" site:opensource.apple.com</a>.</p>  <p>Apple uses it like so, but its not clear to me what they are trying to achieve:</p>  <pre class="lang-c-preprocessor prettyprint-override"><code>#if __DARWIN_C_LEVEL &gt; __DARWIN_C_ANSI #define _POSIX_ARG_MAX      4096 #define _POSIX_CHILD_MAX    25 ... #endif </code></pre>  <p>What is <code>__DARWIN_C_LEVEL</code>, and how should it be used?</p>